<div class="comment-wrapper"><ul class="comments"><li class="comment"><div class="avatar"><img src="https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8809800aec2460f291384b794d7e6f8f?s=50"></div><header><strong>Dollar library, good or not?</strong> from <string>Rick Mann</string> &lt;rmann at latencyzero.com&gt;<p>October 20, 2016 at 03:00:00pm</p></header><div class="content"><p>A discussion on swift-evolution prompted me to look at the Dollar library (https://github.com/ankurp/Dollar). Is this library an example of good design? It doesn&#39;t seem to be to me. No doubt much of the actual functionality is helpful, I&#39;m just asking about the API design.<br></p><p>For example, why is everything hung off a variable (&quot;$&quot;)? Why not just a collection of global methods?<br></p><p>It seems to tout the fact that it&#39;s good because it does NOT extend any built-in objects, but that seems un-swifty.<br></p><p>Thanks,<br></p><p>-- <br>Rick Mann<br>rmann at latencyzero.com<br></p></div><ul class="comments"><li class="comment"><div class="avatar"><img src="https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/02645fccf0e885c607f3d07a4abf4f95?s=50"></div><header><strong>Dollar library, good or not?</strong> from <string>Saagar Jha</string> &lt;saagar at saagarjha.com&gt;<p>October 20, 2016 at 10:00:00pm</p></header><div class="content"><p>IMO no. The author&#39;s Cent library (https://github.com/ankurp/Cent/) though<br>looks a lot &quot;Swift-ier&quot; to me, using extensions rather than a global &quot;$&quot;.<br>On Thu, Oct 20, 2016 at 15:05 Rick Mann via swift-users &lt;<br>swift-users at swift.org&gt; wrote:<br></p><p>&gt; A discussion on swift-evolution prompted me to look at the Dollar library (<br>&gt; https://github.com/ankurp/Dollar). Is this library an example of good<br>&gt; design? It doesn&#39;t seem to be to me. No doubt much of the actual<br>&gt; functionality is helpful, I&#39;m just asking about the API design.<br>&gt;<br>&gt; For example, why is everything hung off a variable (&quot;$&q